## Common Evaluation Errors

### Credentialism Fallacy

Wrong: Source is credible because author has a PhD.

Right: Credentials matter but are not sufficient. Check if credentials are relevant to the claim and if the person has conflicts of interest.

### Appeal to Authority

Wrong: Accept claim because it comes from prestigious institution.

Right: Even prestigious sources make errors. Verify the specific claim, not just the source reputation.

### False Balance

Wrong: Treat fringe views as equivalent to scientific consensus.

Right: Weight sources by evidence quality, not just for "balance." One outlier study doesn't equal hundreds of confirming studies.

### Source Laundering

Wrong: Accept claim because multiple outlets report it.

Right: Trace to original source. Multiple outlets may all be citing the same original (unverified) source.
